AGI - The International Organization for Migration denounces the discovery of at least 65 migrant bodies in a common pit in the southwest of Libya. The circumstances of their death and their nationality "remain unknown", but it is believed that they died "while they were transported clandestinely through the desert", says the Oim.
Every complaint of a missing migrant or a loss of human lives "represents a mourning family seeking answers to their loved ones or recognizing the tragedy of loss", said an Oim spokesman, according to which "the cost of inadequate action is evident in the rise of the dead and in the disturbing conditions in which migrants are located".
This last tragedy highlights the United Nations agency, "the urgent need for a coordinated response to migrant trafficking and trafficking. Without regular routes that offer legal migration opportunities, such tragedies will continue to be a feature along this path." The Oim "appreciates that the Libyan authorities are investigating these deaths and invites them, together with the partner agencies of the United Nations, to ensure dignified recovery, identification and transfer of the remains of the deceased migrants, as well as to properly notify and assist their families". According to the Missing Migrants Project, in 2023 at least 3.129 deaths were recorded and disappeared along the Mediterranean route, "the most deadly migration route". &nbsp;

