AGI - The U.S. Congress has approved, in a rare demonstration of transversal units, a financing law that maintains federal agencies until September and avoids a harmful partial shutdown of the government. Senators did not respect the midnight deadline to approve the $1,200 billion package, which would allow light to be lit in several key government agencies, but voted on early Saturday to approve a resolution that had already been passed to the House. "It is good for the American people that we have reached a bipartisan agreement to finish the job," said the leader of the democratic majority Chuck Schumer in the Senate after hours of thesis.&nbsp negotiations;
&nbsp;
A day of great tension had begun in Capitol Hill when the House of Representatives approved Friday at lunchtime a package of six bills of $1,200 billion, which represents the broadest and most controversial section of federal funding. With the depletion of funds at midnight for three quarters of the government, including defense and internal security, the Senate was forced to a race against time to pass the law on President Joe Biden's desk. However, the negotiations on the budget seemed to break, with both parties pushing to change the legislation so as to reflect the messages and priorities of their election campaign in view of the November presidential elections, when Biden will address former President Donald Trump.&nbsp; The senators were preparing to upgrade without reaching an agreement on the vote, which would prompt the White House Management and Budget Office (OMB) to begin to reduce operations in major federal agencies today. An agreement was reached just when the midnight deadline came and the Senate voted to approve the resolution after 2:00, Washington.&nbsp time;

