AGI - Turkey has stepped up military intervention in northern Iraq after President Recep Tayyip Erdogan > promised "to close the accounts" with Kurdish separatist militiamen of the Pkk>. Wednesday morning the Ankara army announced that the F16s blew up 27 ammunition deposits and shelters of Kurdish separatists, images of the destruction of a vehicle with Rojda Bilen>, one of the chiefs of the Pkk in northern Iraq, hit by a drone. In the same minutes, there was news of 139 suspected members of the organization arrested in 15 different provinces of the country.
&nbsp;
The Ankara reaction arrives after a military was killed last weekend and another 4 wounded in the mountains bordering Turkey and Iraq. A victim who joins the other 12 Turkish soldiers who have lost their lives in northern Iraq over the past few weeks. "We want to secure our border with Iraq before summer and finish work in Syria. We expect everyone in the region to respect our strategy and our need for security. On the contrary, tensions could arise," said Turkish President.&nbsp;
<h2> The difficult relations with Baghdad
A new page of the war between Ankara and Pkk, a conflict begun in 1984 >e for decades fought in the south east and in the rural areas of Turkey, secured in recent years, when the clashes concentrated in the mountainous provinces of northern Iraq. The aim of Ankara is to establish a 30-40 km deep bearing area beyond its border. A possible operation in Syria, due to political uncertainty arising from post-Civil War, but that for Iraq needs the free way of the Baghdad government. The latter has misled the continuing territorial treasury of the F16 in Ankara and protested repeatedly in recent years.
&nbsp;
Last week the head of Turkish intelligence services Ibrahim Kalin>, the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Hakan Fidan> and the Minister of Defense Yasar Guler>, flew to Iraq for a series of meetings aimed at paving the way for an understanding with the Iraqi government and the visit that Erdogan will carry out in Iraq in April. At the end of the visit the two delegations issued a communiqué through which they undertake to collaborate in the fight against the Pkk, called "a threat to the security of both countries" that the Baghdad government now considers "terror organization". The Turkish government, meanwhile, intensified its pressure on the Puk party of Bafel Talabani, to withdraw publicly any form of support to the Pkk in northern Iraq.
<h2 What scenarios if the US withdraws? </h2
A fundamental aspect for the development of the coming months and the common commitment in contrast to the Pkk. Ankara from the end of last November has stepped up operations and does not intend to stop until the constitution of the already mentioned buffer zone. A weapon to convince Baghdad in the hands of Erdogan is the project of infrastructure development that previews the construction of 1,200 kilometers of highway between the Iraqi city of Basra and Turkey. A development plan that can bring money and employment and that goes to Baghdad, to realize that it is necessary to eliminate from different provinces the Pkk. A project that assumes in perspective even more value, in light of the relative uncertainty the safety of marine transport in the Red Sea.
&nbsp;
Another factor to be taken into account is the pressure from the Iraqi government towards the United States. A perspective on which Washington is working; a chance to become more and more concrete if Donald Trump wins the next elections. The withdrawal of US troops would open enormous spaces to Iran to expand its influence in Iraq. A perspective that the Iraqi government can counteract by maximizing the level of collaboration with Turkey.&nbsp;
